display="inline"><![CDATA[H^0(X,\mathcal {O}_X)]]></fr:tex> is a local ring <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex>, and that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[A/\mathfrak {r}(A)]]></fr:tex> is radicial over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>.
    Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> be an algebraic closure of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>, and let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}=X\otimes _k\Omega ]]></fr:tex> (which is connected).
    Pick a geometric point <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {a}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\overline {X}]]></fr:tex> that projects to the geometric point <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.
    Then we have an exact sequence
    <fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[       e       \to  \pi _1(\overline {X},\overline {e})       \to  \pi _1(X,a)       \to  \pi _1(k,b)       \to  e     ]]></fr:tex>
    (where <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(k,b)]]></fr:tex> is the Galois group of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Omega ]]></fr:tex> over <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p>
  
    
